ðŸ“˜ Problem: Allocate Minimum Pages
ðŸ§© Problem Statement:
Given an array arr[] where each element represents the number of pages in a book, and an integer k representing the number of students, allocate books such that:

Each student gets at least one book.

Books are assigned in contiguous order.

No book is assigned to more than one student.

ðŸ” Objective:
Minimize the maximum number of pages assigned to a student.

ðŸ” Constraints:
Contiguous book allocation only.

One student per segment.

A valid allocation is not possible if k > n (students > books).

ðŸ’¡ Concept: Binary Search on Answer
Instead of searching through all combinations (which is very slow), use binary search to minimize the maximum number of pages.

ðŸ“Š Binary Search Boundaries:
Low (start) = max(arr) â†’ Minimum pages any student must get.

High (end) = sum(arr) â†’ All books to one student.

Why?
A student canâ€™t get fewer pages than the biggest book.

One student can read all books, so total pages are the upper limit.

âœ… Core Idea:
We guess a number mid (possible max pages per student) and check:

â“Can we allocate books to k students such that no one gets more than mid pages?

âœ”ï¸ If YES:
Try a smaller value â†’ move high = mid - 1

âŒ If NO:
Increase pages â†’ move low = mid + 1

ðŸ” Check Function: isPossible(arr, n, k, mid)
Steps:
Initialize studentCount = 1 and currentPages = 0

Traverse array:

If arr[i] > mid: âŒ Not possible

If currentPages + arr[i] > mid: Assign to next student

Else: Add to current studentâ€™s pages

Return true if studentCount <= k

ðŸ”  Final Algorithm: findMinimumPages(arr, k)
plaintext
Copy
Edit
1. If k > n, return -1
2. Set low = max(arr), high = sum(arr)
3. Binary Search:
   - mid = (low + high) / 2
   - If isPossible(..., mid) â†’ update result, high = mid - 1
   - Else â†’ low = mid + 1
4. Return result
ðŸ§® Time & Space Complexity:
Component	Complexity
Time	O(n * log(sum - max))
Space	O(1)

ðŸ§ª Example:
